article.headline: Temple 74, Rhode Island 54
article.story: PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- While Temple starter Dustin Salisbery was recovering from the flu, the rest of the Owls more than made up for his absence. Mardy Collins scored 26 points, Mark Tyndale added 14 and Antywane Robinson had 11 as the Owls defeated a depleted Rhode Island team 74-54 on Wednesday. "These are the games we need if we want an at-large bid to the NCAA Tournament," said Collins, who shot 11 of 15 and added four steals. "We lost to Fordham earlier this season, and we can't afford losses like that. We know Rhode Island had injuries, but we just wanted to come out strong and stay on them all game." Tyndale played arguably his finest all-around game all season, adding seven assists, six rebounds and four steals for Temple (10-8, 6-1 Atlantic 10). "He's capable of doing some great things for us," Temple coach John Chaney said. "When he takes off, he turns into Superman at times. He can get to the basket. He's got some quick ups. He's a good athlete, and when he learns to feed off what he's seeing, he's going to be a much better player." Temple scored the first eight points of the game and led by as much as 23 points in the first half. The Owls extended their lead to 28 with 14:41 remaining on the way to defeating the Rams for the 11th straight time. Will Daniels led the Rams (4-14, 2-5) with 11 points while Parfait Bitee added 10. "We knew they had a lot of guys injured and that takes its toll," Robinson said. "We wanted to go out and keep playing, keep fighting, and that's what we did." Rhode Island entered the game with only nine players available. Several others have missed large portions of the season with a variety of injuries. Rhode Island's lack of depth was evident as it shot just 33 percent and committed 14 turnovers. "Anytime you lose three starters, it's tough," Rhode Island coach Jim Baron said. "We had to have other young guys stepping up. They had guys coming in with fresh legs. It kind of wore us down."
